    <!-- Add Activity -->

     <activity>
        <title>Changing the Subject of a Formula</title>
        <statement>
<p>Work in groups</p>
<p>What you need:</p>
<p>Paper, pencil, and a calculator.</p>
<p>What to do:</p>
<ol>
<li>
<p>Consider the formula: <m>v = u + at</m></p>
<ul>
<li>Identify the subject of the formula.</li>
<li>What does each letter represent?</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>
<p>Suppose you want to make <m>t</m> the subject of the formula.</p>
<ul>
<li>Work step by step to rearrange the formula.</li>
<li>Write down each step clearly.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>
<p>Compare your steps with another group.</p>
<ul>
<li>Did you follow the same process?</li>
<li>If not, discuss the differences.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>
<p>Use your new formula to complete the table:</p>
<tabular>
<row><cell><m>v</m></cell><cell><m>u</m></cell><cell><m>a</m></cell><cell><m>t</m></cell></row>
<row><cell>15</cell><cell>3</cell><cell>2</cell><cell></cell></row>
<row><cell>20</cell><cell>4</cell><cell>4</cell><cell></cell></row>
<row><cell>18</cell><cell>6</cell><cell>3</cell><cell></cell></row>
</tabular>
</li>
<li>
<p>What pattern do you notice in the steps you used to make <m>t</m> the subject?</p>
<ul>
<li>Describe a general method for changing the subject of a formula.</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ol>
<p>Make <m>u</m> the subject of the formula <m>v = u + at</m>.</p>
<p>Share your findings with the class.</p>
        </statement>
    </activity>

